    "blog_two_col_intro": {
      "type": "blog-two-column-text",
      "name": "Blog: Two Column Text",
      "settings": {
        "width": "wrapper--full",
        "max_width": 1100,
        "gap": 100,
        "left_heading": "Roberto Coin has traveled the world in search of beautiful inspirations for the jewelry that bears his name.",
        "left_text": "",
        "left_text_style": "body",
        "left_italic": false,
        "right_heading": "",
        "right_text": "<p>\"I find beauty everywhere,\" he says, \"in nature, in people, in architecture, in art and in food.\" His collections reflect this: since 1996, he's drawn inspiration from diverse sources—from the natural world in Animalier to the stars in his Zodiac Medallions.<br/><br/>Few places inspire Coin like his native Italy. Walking through Verona with Roberto, you'll notice him pausing constantly to admire details—the rosoni medallions on building facades, the red brick merlons of Castelvecchio, the Ponte Pietra, a Roman bridge from around 100 BC still in use today. \"Even when I'm by myself, I am never alone,\" he says. \"Walking through this city is like watching a film—I can see what it used to be in those days.\"<br/><br/>Today, in Verona, the città dell'amore, he shares his process, philosophy, and the origins of his new \"Love in Verona\" collection.</p>",
        "right_text_style": "body",
        "right_italic": true,
        "padding_top": 120,
        "padding_bottom": 0,
        "padding_top_mobile": 60,
        "padding_bottom_mobile": 0
      }
    },
